","Ormesby St Michael, Norfolk, England":"Ormesby St Michael, Norfolk, England","Boxted, Essex, England":"Boxted, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Page","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and French: occupational or status name for a young servant, Middle English <i>page</i>, <i>paige</i>, Old French <i>page</i> (from Italian <i>paggio</i>, ultimately from Greek <i>paidion</i>, a diminutive of <i>pais</i> ‘boy, child’). The surname has also been established in Ireland since the 16th century. In North America, this surname is also a shortened form of the French cognate   Lepage  .","French Canadian (<b>Pagé</b>): altered form of French   Paget  , a diminutive of 1. Compare   Pashia  .","North German: metonymic occupational name for a horse dealer, from Middle Low German <i>page</i> ‘horse’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pages","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Mario, Eduardo, Jorge, Luis, Mauricio, Ramon, Fernando, Jose, Lazaro, Pedro, Alfredo.  French Jacques, Lucien, Michel.","Catalan and southern French (<b>Pagès</b>): occupational name for a peasant farmer or agricultural laborer, from Catalan and Old Occitan <i>pagès</i> ‘peasant’ (from Late Latin <i>pagensis</i>, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘village, country district’).","English: variant of   Page   with genitival of post-medieval excrescent <i>s</i>."]},{"name":"Paget","meanings":["French: diminutive of   Page  .","English: variant of   Padgett  ."]},{"name":"Paige","meanings":["English (mainly Devon): variant of   Page  ."]},{"name":"Pageau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Stephane, Alphonse, Andre, Fernand, Gisele, Jean Claude, Lucien, Philippe.","French: diminutive of   Page  ."]},{"name":"Lepage","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Fernand, Pierre, Raoul, Adelard, Alcide, Christophe, Lucien, Normand, Adrien.","French: occupational or status name for a young servant, a variant of   Page   1, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. Compare   Lapage  .","French Canadian: altered form of <b>Pagé</b> (see   Page   2)."]},{"name":"Padgett","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire): from a Middle English diminutive of <i>page</i>, <i>paige</i> ‘servant, groom’ (see   Page  )."]},{"name":"Littlepage","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>littel</i> ‘small’ +Middle English, Old French <i>page</i> ‘young servant’ (see   Page  )."]},{"name":"Pashia","meanings":["Americanized form of French Canadian <b>Pagé</b> (see   Page   2).","History: It was Jean Baptiste Pagé from QC whose surname was changed to <i>Pashia</i> after he settled in MO in the 1810s. Some of his descendants bear a rare variant, <i>Pashea</i>."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":4,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":6,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":20,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":22,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":35,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Robert Page was born in 1565, in Boxted, Essex, England. He had at least 2 sons with Susanna Syckerlyn. He died on 13 November 1605, in his hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1 Jan 1565–13 Nov 1605":"1565–13. november 1605","1566–1607":"1566–1607","1586–1676":"1586–1676","1605–1676":"1605–1676","1565–1605":"1565–1605","1 Jan 1565":"1565","13 Nov 1605":"13. november 1605","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1 May 1605":"1. mai 1605","1676":"1676","1566":"1566","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1586":"1586","1585":"1585","1607":"1607","25 Sep 1586":"25. september 1586","1605":"1605","Harwich, Essex, England":"Harwich, Essex, England","Ormesby St Michael, Norfolk, England":"Ormesby St Michael, Norfolk, England"